Emit a `show` event immediately and use `mergeMap` with a delayed `of` to schedule the `dismiss` event. Because `mergeMap` runs inner observables concurrently, multiple toasts can overlap without one blocking the next.

```typescript
import { Subject, Observable, mergeMap, of, delay, merge, map } from "rxjs";

interface Toast { id: string; text: string; }
type TEvt = { kind: "show" | "dismiss"; id: string; text?: string };

const in$ = new Subject<Toast>();

const out$: Observable<TEvt> = in$.pipe(
  mergeMap((t: Toast) =>
    merge(
      of<TEvt>({ kind: "show", id: t.id, text: t.text }),
      of<TEvt>({ kind: "dismiss", id: t.id }).pipe(delay(3000))
    )
  ),
  map((e: TEvt) => e)
);

out$.subscribe((e: TEvt) => { void e; });
```

Each incoming toast is mapped to a two-emission inner observable: an immediate `show` event and a `dismiss` event delayed by the toast's TTL. `mergeMap` runs these inner observables concurrently so one slow toast doesn't hold up others. The outer stream becomes a flat sequence of show/dismiss events ready for the UI reducer.

